Warning


What went wrong? The file has 9 rows of metadata before the actual data begins. read_excel() read the first row as column headers – giving us nonsense names like ...2, ...4, Tonnes per capita.
This is extremely common with official statistical releases (Eurostat, World Bank, UN). Always inspect your file before loading.

End-to-End: Import, Clean, Reshape, Join

The complete pipeline – this is what your homework setup code will look like:


View source
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(janitor)

# --- GHG: skip 9 metadata rows, clean names, pivot ---
ghg &lt;- read_excel("data/Eurostat_GHGpc.xlsx", sheet = "Sheet 1", skip = 9) |&gt;
  clean_names() |&gt;
  rename(country = time) |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(country), !country %in% c("Special value", ":")) |&gt;
  select(-x2019) |&gt;
  pivot_longer(-country, names_to = "year", values_to = "ghg_pc") |&gt;
  mutate(year = as.integer(str_remove(year, "^x")))

# --- GDP: skip 8 metadata rows, clean names, pivot ---
gdp &lt;- read_excel("data/Eurostat_GDPpc.xlsx", sheet = "Sheet 1", skip = 8) |&gt;
  clean_names() |&gt;
  rename(country = time) |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(country)) |&gt;
  pivot_longer(-country, names_to = "year", values_to = "gdp_pc") |&gt;
  mutate(year = as.integer(str_remove(year, "^x")))

# --- Join on country + year ---
eu_data &lt;- left_join(ghg, gdp, by = c("country", "year"))




